\begin_layout Standard
This is a lot to take in.
 Which is why half the problem set is about running versions of this code
 with different parameter values.
 On my mac, the code runs for a little less than 20 minutes.
 If you got an older machine, it might run a lot slower.
 What takes time is finding the equilibrium interest rate using the bisection
 method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take note of two important final remarks.
 First, this code is not perfect.
 It is not optimized for speed, nor for elegance.
 I tried to write a simple straightforward version of the application.
 The goal is to understand what is going on, and I left a lot of remarks
 all over the code hoping that it might be helpful.
 Once you understand how the algorithm works you can move on to more sophisticat
ed methods in your own research.
 If you do that, recall the endogenous grid method.
 Matt Rognlie (Northwestern) and coauthors also provide a bunch of code,
 which is much closer to the frontier than what I do here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, small errors are extremely costly and hard to find.
 As you start working on this, take your time and try to be as careful as
 possible.
 
